Here are both approaches:

**1. Navigate with a string parameter (product ID):**

```csharp
// From ProductListPage (or its ViewModel)
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"{nameof(ProductDetailsPage)}?productId={product.Id}");
```

**2. Navigate with a complex object:**

```csharp
var navParams = new Dictionary<string, object>
{
    { "product", selectedProduct }
};
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync(nameof(ProductDetailsPage), navParams);
```

**Receiving both on the ViewModel with `IQueryAttributable`:**

```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach 1: string parameter (arrives as string)
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var idObj) && idObj is string id)
        {
            // Load product from a service using the ID
            LoadProduct(id);
        }

        // Approach 2: full object (arrives as the original type)
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product product)
        {
            // Use directly — no deserialization needed
            CurrentProduct = product;
        }
    }
}
```

**Wire the ViewModel to the page:**

```csharp
// ProductDetailsPage.xaml.cs
public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
{
    InitializeComponent();
    BindingContext = vm;
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | String param | Object param |
|---|---|---|
| **Syntax** | interpolated query string | `Dictionary<string, object>` overload |
| **Type in handler** | `string` | original CLR type (`Product`) |
| **Survives URI** | ✅ yes | ❌ not URI-safe, in-memory only |
| **Best for** | deep links, simple IDs | avoiding an extra DB/API lookup |

Both paths converge in the single `ApplyQueryAttributes` method, so you can support either navigation style from the same target page.
